sentences: The 1910 Fruitgum Company is an American bubblegum pop band of the 1960s.
The band began as Jeckell and The Hydes in New Jersey in 1966.

During 1967, they were signed to Buddah Records, where they released five LPs under their own name and a variety of singles, as well as appearing on the LP The Kasenetz-Katz Singing Orchestral Circus, which sounded like the usual Buddah studio band in spite of its promotion as a "bubblegum superjam".
The track peaked at #2 on the UK Singles Chart and was heard in the 1968 Frederick Wiseman documentary High School.
In 1999, original member Frank Jeckell and Mick Mansueto put the act back together.
As of 2019, Fruitgum currently performs its own hits, in addition to other songs from the 1960s.

The 1910 Fruitgum Company is an American bubblegum pop band of the 1960s.
The group's Billboard Hot 100 hits were "Simon Says", "May I Take a Giant Step", "1, 2, 3, Red Light", "Goody Goody Gumdrops", "Indian Giver", "Special Delivery", and "The Train".

They also released these other chart hits: "May I Take a Giant Step" (U.S. #63), "1, 2, 3, Red Light" (U.S. #5), "Special Delivery" (U.S. #38), "Goody, Goody Gumdrops" (U.S. #37), "Indian Giver" (U.S. #5) and "The Train" (U.S. #57).
